Aliasing with a one-to-many relationship can cause duplicate rows in your query results due to the nature of how joins work in SQL. When you join two tables where one table (the "one" side) has a unique identifier and the other table (the "many" side) has multiple entries corresponding to that identifier, each entry from the "many" side will be duplicated for each matching entry in the "one" side.

For example, consider a scenario where you have a `Users` table (one side) and an `Orders` table (many side). If a user has placed multiple orders, joining these tables on the user ID will result in multiple rows for that user—one for each order they have placed. This is what leads to the appearance of duplicate rows in your result set.
